SYSTEM SCALABILITY

1. Scalability

* Ability of a system to handle increasing users, requests, or data without major performance degradation.
* Scalability mainly focuses on increasing throughput by adding hardware resources.

-----------------------------------------

2. Performance vs Scalability

Performance

* Low Latency
* High Throughput
* Concurrency

Scalability

* Ability to increase throughput by adding resources.
* Can scale UP or DOWN according to load.

--------------------------------------------------

3. Types of Scalability

A. Vertical Scaling (Scale Up)

* Increase resources of same machine.
* Add more CPU, RAM, SSD.
* Easier to implement.
* Limited scalability.

Example:
4 CPU, 16 GB RAM
↓
32 CPU, 256 GB RAM

B. Horizontal Scaling (Scale Out)

* Add more servers/machines.
* Load distributed among multiple servers.
* Harder to implement.
* Almost unlimited scalability.

Example:
Server 1
↓
Server 1 + Server 2 + Server 3

-----------------------------------------------------------

4. Reverse Proxy

* Single entry point for clients.
* Routes requests to backend servers.
* Can also act as a Load Balancer.

Client
↓
Reverse Proxy
↓
Multiple Servers

-----------------------------------------------------------

5. Scalability Principles

A. Decentralization

* Avoid monolithic architecture.
* Distribute workload among multiple workers/services.

B. Independence

* Components should work independently.
* Maximum concurrent processing.
* Avoid:
  • Shared Resources
  • Shared Mutable Data

C. Modularity

* Divide system into smaller modules/services.
* Easier maintenance and scaling.

Example:
User Service
Catalog Service
Order Service
Inventory Service

-----------------------------------

6. Replication

* Creating multiple copies to handle increasing workload.

Types:

A. Stateless Replication

* Only code is replicated.
* No session/state stored locally.
* Easier to scale.

B. Stateful Replication

* Code and state both replicated.
* Sessions stored on servers.
* More complex.

---

7. Web Replication

A. Stateful Web Replication

* Session stored on web server.
* Uses Sticky Sessions / Session Affinity.
* Higher performance.
* Lower scalability.

B. Stateless Web Replication

* Session stored outside server.
* Client-side Cookies OR Redis/Memcached.
* Higher scalability.
* Slightly higher latency.

-------------------------------------------------------------

